page.title: 14Woodland near Guyzance.
page.content: The dominant mature trees in this patch of woodland covering the banks of a small stream consist of ash, sycamore and silver birch.There were originally elm trees in the wood but ten of these now stand dead or dying. The mature trees are nearly all acting as hosts to ivy plants which surround the trunks and climb to the highest branches.The wood also contains a few specimans of holly,hawthorn,elder and Norway spruce.At the edges of the wood dog-rose,cherry and bramble may be found.Part of the wood has recently been felled;replanting with ash,sycamore,mountain ash,cherry and at least one copper beech has now taken place.These new trees are protected from rabbits and deer by corrugated plastic tubes.
